    "reasoning": "1. Analyze the provided waveform data to identify the circuit behavior:\n   - Time 5ns: clk=1, a=1 -> q=4 (binary 100)\n   - Time 55ns: clk=1, a=0 -> q=5 (binary 101)\n   - Time 65ns: clk=1, a=0 -> q=6 (binary 110)\n   - Time 75ns: clk=1, a=0 -> q=0 (binary 000)\n   - Time 85ns: clk=1, a=0 -> q=1 (binary 001)\n\n   Looking at the transitions when clk is high (posedge) and 'a' changes:\n   - When a=1: q stays at 4 (from 5ns to 45ns).\n   - When a=0 (after a=1): q sequence is 4 -> 5 -> 6 -> 0 -> 1 -> ...\n   - This looks like an incrementer that starts/resets to 4 when a=1, and increments by 1 when a=0.\n\n2. Refined Logic:\n   - If a == 1: q <= 4 (binary 100).\n   - If a == 0: q <= (q + 1) mod 8 (3-bit wrap around).\n\n3. Let's verify the sequence:\n   - Start: q=4 (at 5ns, a=1)\n   - a=1 continues: q=4\n   - a=0 occurs (45ns): at next clk (55ns), q becomes 5.\n   - a=0 continues: at 65ns, q becomes 6.\n   - a=0 continues: at 75ns, q becomes 0 (wrap around).\n   - a=0 continues: at 85ns, q becomes 1.\n   This matches the waveform perfectly.\n\n4. Implementation Steps:\n   - Use a 3-bit logic register for q.\n   - Use an always block triggered by posedge clk.\n   - Implement the conditional logic: if (a) q <= 3'd4; else q <= q + 1'b1;\n   - Since no reset is specified in the interface, use an initial block to initialize q to 0 to avoid X in simulation.\n\n5. Advice to avoid syntax errors:\n   - Ensure the bit-width of 'q' is exactly [2:0].\n   - Use 'logic' for all declarations.\n   - Ensure the module name is exactly 'TopModule'.\n   - Use always @(*) for combinational if needed, though here we can do it all in one sequential block.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic a,\n    output logic [2:0] q\n);\n\n    // Initialize q to a known value to avoid X\n    initial begin\n        q = 3'b000;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic implementation\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (a) begin\n            // When a is 1, q is set to 4\n            q <= 3'd4;\n        end else begin\n            // When a is 0, q increments (with 3-bit wrap around)\n            q <= q + 3'd1;\n        end\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
